{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0.04,0.08,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72927"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9102"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72927"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDelirium is an acute confusional state commonly encountered in hospital settings, particularly among older patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristic features of delirium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Attention is impaired and fluctuates; recent and immediate memory is impaired; thinking is disorganised","Thinking is disorganised; recent memory is impaired; orientation remains normal","Thinking is intact but hopeless; recent and remote memory are impaired; orientation is poor","Attention and thinking remain normal; perception is intact; mood is low","Behaviour remains normal; perception is intact; all memory is impaired"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cardinal features of delirium include \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpaired and fluctuating attention, impaired recent and immediate memory, and disorganised thinking\u003C/strong\u003E. These features develop acutely and tend to fluctuate throughout the day, often worsening at night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following features are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisorganised thinking with normal orientation\u003C/strong\u003E - Orientation is typically impaired in delirium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntact thinking with hopelessness and memory impairment\u003C/strong\u003E - These features better describe depression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal attention and thinking with intact perception\u003C/strong\u003E - Attention is characteristically impaired in delirium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal behaviour and intact perception\u003C/strong\u003E - Behaviour is often disturbed and perceptual disturbances are common in delirium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelirium represents an acute change in mental status characterised by inattention and global cognitive dysfunction. It is often triggered by medical conditions, medications, or environmental changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delirium is characterised by fluctuating attention, impaired recent/immediate memory, and disorganised thinking.","The key diagnostic features of delirium include acute onset, fluctuating course, inattention, and disorganized thinking.","Delirium differs from dementia by its acute onset and fluctuating course."],"references":["Pisani MA, D\u0027Ambrosio C. Sleep and Delirium in Adults Who Are Critically Ill: A Contemporary Review. Chest. 2020 Apr;157(4):977-984. doi: 10.1016/j.chest.2019.12.003. Epub 2019 Dec 23. PMID: 31874132","Wilson JE, Mart MF, Cunningham C, Shehabi Y, Girard TD, MacLullich AMJ, Slooter AJC, Ely EW. Delirium. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Nov 12;6(1):90. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00223-4. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Dec 1;6(1):94. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00236-z. PMID: 33184265; PMCID: PMC9012267","Wilson JE, Mart MF, Cunningham C, Shehabi Y, Girard TD, MacLullich AMJ, Slooter AJC, Ely EW. Delirium. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Nov 12;6(1):90. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00223-4. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Dec 1;6(1):94. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00236-z. PMID: 33184265; PMCID: PMC9012267","Fong TG, Tulebaev SR, Inouye SK. Delirium in elderly adults: diagnosis, prevention and treatment. Nat Rev Neurol. 2009 Apr;5(4):210-20. doi: 10.1038/nrneurol.2009.24. PMID: 19347026; PMCID: PMC3065676"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58397"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58397"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T19:03:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:24:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9102"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72927"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t